  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm sure he'll come. I received a phone call from him yesterday.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
An expectation that something will not be the case can be expressed by negating the sentence before @HI{{@EM{{hazu}}}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{kura-ku}}sanha@KT{{pa-texi-}}ni@KJ{{going}}kanai@EM{{hazu}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I expect that Mr. Clark is going to the party.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Alternatively the sentence can be followed by <a href="grammar-hazu-ga-nai.html">@HI{{@EM{{hazu}}}}@HI{{ha/ganai}}</a>.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{kura-ku}}sanha@KT{{pa-texi-}}ni@KJ{{going}}ku@EM{{hazu}}ganai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It is improbable that Mr. Clark will go to the party.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The latter construction carries the heavier weight.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
